      <h2>What Is ENT?</h2>
      <p>
        <strong>Emergent Necessity Theory (ENT)</strong> proposes that structure and order in complex systems emerge not randomly, but as a <b>necessary</b> mathematical consequence once a system’s internal coherence reaches a universal threshold.
      </p>
      <a href="accessible.html" class="cta">Read the Accessible Version &rarr;</a>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2>The Core Equation</h2>
      <pre class="formula">
τ = (∑ I(xᵢ; xⱼ) − E(X)) / E(X)
      </pre>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>I(xᵢ; xⱼ)</strong>: Mutual information between subsystems</li>
        <li><strong>E(X)</strong>: Entropy of the global system</li>
        <li><strong>τ<sub>c</sub></strong>: Critical threshold value (e.g., τ ≈ 1.5)</li>
      </ul>
      <p>When τ &ge; τ<sub>c</sub>, organized structure emerges as a necessity.</p>
    </section>
