  <header>
    <h1>ENT: Core Theory</h1>
    <nav>
      <a href="index.html">Home</a> |
      <a href="accessible.html">ENT for Everyone</a> |
      <a href="simulations.html">Simulations</a>
    </nav>
  </header>
  <main>
    <section>
      <h2>Universal Coherence Threshold</h2>
      <p>
        ENT is built on a universal threshold: whenever the internal coherence of a system, measured by the collective mutual information between its parts, exceeds a critical value (τ<sub>c</sub>), structure <strong>must</strong> emerge.
      </p>
      <pre class="formula">
τ = (∑ I(xᵢ; xⱼ) − E(X)) / E(X)
      </pre>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>I(xᵢ; xⱼ)</strong> = Mutual information between subsystems</li>
        <li><strong>E(X)</strong> = Total system entropy</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If τ ≥ τ<sub>c</sub> (universal threshold, often 1.5 in models), phase transition occurs: new order is unavoidable.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2>Mathematical Details</h2>
      <p>
        The threshold τ<sub>c</sub> predicts phase transitions in complex systems, from quantum fields to brain networks. Learn more in the <a href="https://zenodo.org/records/15939045" target="_blank">latest Zenodo paper</a> or <a href="resources.html">Resources</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
    <section>
      <h2>Compare: Necessity vs. Probability</h2>
      <p>
        Traditional emergence: structure probably appears.<br />
        ENT: structure <b>necessarily</b> appears above threshold.<br />
        (<a href="accessible.html#faq">FAQ</a> for more.)
      </p>
    </section>
  </main>
